{"key":"post-15831553","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15831553</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;ow comes the question (finally):&amp;nbsp; My agar must be poured warm to avoid setting-up while still in the flask.&amp;nbsp; I have read warnings about removing the rocker too quickly.&amp;nbsp; Can I assume the if I measure the outside temperature of the PC with the non-contact infrared thermometer, remove the rocker and open the PC lid at about 150Â°F, I will be below the point of boil-over while still warm enough to pour the agar?&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;An infrared thermometer is useless for pointing at a pressure cooker.&amp;nbsp; It will only read the outside surface temperature which is exposed to the much cooler air and not the inside temperature.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;However, that's not when your agar is boiling over.&amp;nbsp; It boils over during sterilization if you allow the weight to jiggle, or after sterilization if you allow the unit to lose pressure too slowly.&amp;nbsp; At the end of the cycle as the unit is dropping pressure, always turn your stove back on a few times to slow the process.&amp;nbsp; You want to drop from 15 psi to 0 psi as slowly as possible.&amp;nbsp; I use my AA921 for agar, and I make sure it takes nearly half an hour to go from 15 psi to zero.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I have 4 AA75X sterilizers, which I use for grains.&amp;nbsp; They're not suitable for agar unless you're right there when zero psi is reached to open the unit up.&amp;nbsp; If a vacuum is pulled, that will cause the agar to boil over too, and sterilizers always pull a vacuum as they cool.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15833206</next>\n<prev>15831528</prev>\n<first>15831269</first>\n<last>15837187</last>\n<when>1329672245</when>\n<utime>02/19/12 07:24 PM</utime>\n</post>"}